{
  "answer": "**Tarānā-e-Millī** (Bang-e-Dara Part 3, ch. 23) asserts a singular *millat* (Muslim community/nation) open to all who share its defining conviction, proclaiming: \"From Chin to Arab lands, our story flows, / The whole wide world's the home a Muslim knows.\"[^1] This defines collective identity geographically expansive and unified under Islam.[^2]\n\n**Manusmṛti** Book 1 asserts four *varṇas* (social orders) as innately distributed by divine origin at creation: \"And for the sake of the prosperity of the worlds, he caused the Brahmana, the Kshatriya, the Vaishya, and the Shudra to emanate from his mouth, arms, thighs, and feet.\"[^3] The text frames this as primordial and hierarchical, with laws specified \"for all the four *varnas* (social orders) and for those born between them,\" and the Shudra's role as serving the others.[^4]\n\nBoth texts claim binding collective identities for social order. The asymmetry—*millat* open by conviction, *varṇas* closed by birth—is visible in **Tarānā-e-Millī**'s verse tying membership to faith alone: \"The sacred trust of One God fills our soul, / No force can wipe our name from history's scroll,\"[^5] with no birth prerequisite, unlike Manu's emanation from body parts.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 (*Tarana-e-Milli*), [p-8a4681](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-8a4681).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 (*Tarana-e-Milli*), [p-882645](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-882645).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, ch. 1, [p-13a2db](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-13a2db).\n\n[^4]: *Manusmṛti*, ch. 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-b51d68#p-26a572).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, ch. 23 (*Tarana-e-Milli*), [p-882645](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/23-tarana-e-milli/translation/#p-882645).",
